      "Either `p₃ c`, then `p₂ c` is false (because `p₂ c` requires `¬p₃ c`).\n   - Or `¬p₃ c`, then `p₂ c` holds.\n\nThus, exactly one of `p₁ c`, `p₂ c`, `p₃ c` holds for any given `c`.\n\nThen we just need:\n`(S.filter p₁).length + (S.filter p₂).length + (S.filter p₃).length = S.length`\n\nBut in Lean, `List.filter p S` returns `S` elements satisfying `p`, and if every element of `S` satisfies exactly one of `p₁`, `p₂`, `p₃`, then summing the lengths will give `S.length`.\n\nBut to prove `S.length = initPart.length + midPart.length + finalPart.length`, we can instead just use that for every `c ∈ S`, exactly one of the three conditions holds.\n\nBut in Lean, to do that, we can instead use:\n`S.length = (S.filter p₁ ++ S.filter p₂ ++ S.filter p₃).length` when the three filters are pairwise disjoint and their union is `S`, but it is easier to realize that the three filters partition `S`. \n\nBut perhaps we have not yet formalized that `p₁`, `p₂`, `p₃` partition `S`. \n\nAlternatively, we can instead prove that for each `c ∈ S`, `(c ∈ initPart) ⊕ (c ∈ midPart) ⊕ (c ∈ finalPart)`, i.e., exactly one is true, and thus we get that the sum of lengths is `S.length`.\n\nBut to avoid this complication, perhaps we should instead use `List.filter` to form `initPart`, `midPart`, `finalPart`, and then note that `midPart` can be written as `S.filter (fun c => ¬(isInitialCall m S c) ∧ ¬(isFinalCall m S c))`. \n\nNow, observe that for any `c ∈ S`, either `isInitialCall m S c` or not.\n\nIf it is true, then `c ∈ initPart`. If it is false, then either `isFinalCall m S c` is true, and thus `c ∈ finalPart`, or it is false, and then `c ∈ midPart`.\n\nThus, every element of `S` is in exactly one of `initPart`, `midPart`, `finalPart`, because `p₁`, `p₂`, `p₃` are exclusive and exhaustive.\n\nHence, `initPart.length + midPart.length + finalPart.length = S.length`.\n\nBut Lean does not have a direct lemma for this, so perhaps we should instead show that `initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart = S`, and that the three parts are disjoint.\n\nBut, perhaps it is easier to instead use that for every element `c` in `S`, exactly one of `p₁ c`, `p₂ c`, `p₃ c` is true.\n\nThus, in Lean, we can use the following approach: iterate through each element of `S`, and count how many times it appears in each of `initPart`, `midPart`, `finalPart`. \n\nBut perhaps another approach is to realize that the `midPart` can actually be written as `S.filter (fun c => ¬isInitialCall m S c ∧ ¬isFinalCall m S c)` and that the union of the three parts is `S`. \n\nAlternatively, we can use that if the three parts are pairwise disjoint, and every element of `S` is in exactly one of them, then their lengths add up.\n\nBut perhaps we can work directly using `List.filter`, because we can use that `S.length = (S.filter p₁).length + (S.filter (¬p₁)).length`, and then repeat for `p₃`, but this seems complicated.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use that any `c ∈ S` falls into exactly one of `initPart`, `midPart`, or `finalPart`, and use this to count the length.\n\nBut, given that this is quite involved, perhaps there is an easier way to get that `(initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart).length = S.length` when every element of `S` is in exactly one of them.\n\nBut perhaps there is an even easier way: For every `c ∈ S`, it is counted once in exactly one of the three parts, so the sum of lengths is `S.length`.\n\nBut in Lean, to formalize that we need to get:\n`initPart.length + midPart.length + finalPart.length = S.length`.\n\nBut perhaps we can use `Finset` and `Multiset` to make it easier: convert `S` to a `Multiset`, and then sum the lengths by partitioning.\n\nBut instead, we can use the following idea:\n1. For each element of `S`, we have that it is in exactly one of the three parts.\n2. Hence, `initPart.length + midPart.length + finalPart.length` counts each element of `S` exactly once, so it equals `S.length`.\n\nBut perhaps instead we can use the following partitioning:\n\nFor all `c ∈ S`, exactly one of:\n`isInitialCall m S c`, `¬isInitialCall m S c ∧ is",
      "\n    have h₁ : initPart.length + midPart.length + finalPart.length = S.length := by\n      have h₂ : initPart.length + midPart.length + finalPart.length = (initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart).length := by\n        simp [List.length_append]\n        <;> ring\n      have h₃ : initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart = S := by\n        have h₄ : ∀ c ∈ S, c ∈ initPart ∨ c ∈ midPart ∨ c ∈ finalPart := by\n          intro c hc\n          have h₅ : (isInitialCall m S c &&& true) || (¬isInitialCall m S c &&& isFinalCall m S c &&& true) || (¬isInitialCall m S c &&& ¬isFinalCall m S c &&& true) := by\n            simp [isInitialCall, isFinalCall, isAgentInitialCall, isAgentFinalCall, List.find?]\n            <;>\n            (try decide) <;>\n            (try omega) <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                by_cases h₆ : c.fst = c.fst\n                <;> simp_all [List.find?, Nat.lt_succ_iff]\n                <;> aesop\n              }) <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                by_cases h₆ : c.snd = c.snd\n                <;> simp_all [List.find?, Nat.lt_succ_iff]\n                <;> aesop\n              })\n          simp_all [initPart, midPart, finalPart, List.mem_filter, isInitialCall, isFinalCall]\n          <;>\n          (try omega) <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              by_cases h₆ : c.fst = c.fst\n              <;> simp_all [List.find?, Nat.lt_succ_iff]\n              <;> aesop\n            }) <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              by_cases h₆ : c.snd = c.snd\n              <;> simp_all [List.find?, Nat.lt_succ_iff]\n              <;> aesop\n            })\n        have h₅ : initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart = S := by\n          apply List.Sublist.ext\n          · -- Prove that initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart is a sublist of S\n            have h₆ : initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart = initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart := rfl\n            have h₇ : initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart ⊆ S := by\n              intro x hx\n              simp only [List.mem_append, List.mem_filter] at hx ⊢\n              aesop\n            exact h₇\n          · -- Prove that S is a sublist of initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart\n            have h₆ : S ⊆ initPart ++ midPart ++ finalPart := by\n              intro x hx\n              have h₇ : x ∈ initPart ∨ x ∈ midPart ∨ x ∈ finalPart := h₄ x hx\n              simp only [List.mem_append, List.mem_filter] at h₇ ⊢\n              aesop\n            exact h₆\n        exact h₅\n      rw [h₃] at *\n      <;> simp_all [List.length_append]\n      <;> ring\n    linarith",
